# Principles

Three rules govern every change in this codebase. When in doubt, default to the simpler option.

## 1. Keep It Simple

- Prefer the most boring solution that works. No clever tricks.
- Use the framework's defaults (Next.js App Router conventions, shadcn primitives as-is) before reaching for custom code.
- One file, one purpose. Don't introduce abstractions until there are at least two concrete callers.
- Inline a value or component until duplication forces extraction — not before.

```tsx
// BAD — premature abstraction, custom hook for one consumer
const useHeading = (text: string) => useMemo(() => text.toUpperCase(), [text]);

// GOOD — inline, obvious
<h1>{title.toUpperCase()}</h1>
```

## 2. Less Is More

- Ship fewer components, fewer props, fewer dependencies.
- Reuse existing shadcn/ui components and Tailwind utilities before writing new CSS or installing new packages.
- Trim props with sensible defaults; avoid optional booleans that toggle styling — compose instead.
- Delete dead code, unused imports, and commented-out blocks as you go.
- Resist adding a new file when an existing one is the right home.

```tsx
// BAD — flag soup
<Card padded bordered shadow rounded fullWidth />

// GOOD — sane defaults, compose when needed
<Card className="w-full" />
```

## 3. Mobile First

- Design and write layouts for the smallest viewport first, then layer up with Tailwind breakpoint prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`).
- Unprefixed utilities are the mobile baseline. Never start from desktop and patch downwards.
- Use fluid sizing (`%`, `rem`, `min()`/`max()`/`clamp()`) over fixed pixel widths.
- Tap targets ≥ 44px, readable body text ≥ 16px, no horizontal scroll on narrow screens.

```tsx
// BAD — desktop-first, fights itself on mobile
<div className="flex flex-row gap-8 max-md:flex-col max-md:gap-2" />

// GOOD — mobile-first, scales up
<div className="flex flex-col gap-2 md:flex-row md:gap-8" />
```
